{
  "query": "How do different management approaches for uncropped arable field margins in Europe, such as sowing mixes versus natural regeneration, compare in their benefits for bumblebees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across replicated European and UK trials, sown margins generally supported more foraging bumblebees than naturally regenerated margins: margins sown with agricultural nectar/pollen mixes, especially perennial legumes, attracted significantly more foraging bumblebees than naturally regenerated, grassy, or cropped margins in multiple trials, though value degraded over time and required re-sowing every few years (18). Margins sown with native wildflower mixes and subsequently mown supported higher bumblebee abundance (and in three trials higher species richness) than cropped, grassy, or naturally regenerated margins in several trials (19). In contrast, naturally regenerated uncropped margins sometimes had more bumblebees (and in two trials more species) than cropped margins, but evidence was mixed, including trials finding no higher abundance or diversity than cropped margins; benefits varied year-to-year and often depended on thistles that may require control (20). Comparisons between seed mix types were mixed: a mix of agricultural forage plants including legumes attracted greater numbers of bumblebees than a perennial wildflower mix in the first year in one trial (18), whereas one small replicated trial found common long\u2011tongued bumblebees preferred perennial wildflower plots over annual forage plant mixes (19). A small unreplicated study recorded similar bee species richness on wildflower\u2011sown versus naturally regenerated strips (19, 20).",
