{
  "query": "What factors are known to influence the occupancy and productivity of artificial nest sites provided for solitary bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "- Proximity to forage influenced use: studies recommend placing nest boxes within 150\u2013600 m of foraging resources (47; 80).\n- Nesting material and design affected productivity: reed stems and wooden grooved-board designs produced more bees per nest than several other types, while plastic-lined holes and plastic/paper tubes were less productive due to parasitism or mould; for Centris analis, cardboard straws in drilled wooden holes outperformed grooved wooden boards (47; 80).\n- Repeated provision over multiple years increased occupancy: the number of occupied solitary bee nests nearly doubled over three years at sites with continued nest box provision, and local populations/emergence of red mason bees increased where boxes were provided (47; 80).\n- Reported occupancy rates for solitary bee nest boxes ranged from 1% to 26% of available cavities across replicated studies (80).\n- Predators and parasites influenced outcomes: multiple trials recorded attacks and variable mortality/parasitism rates in nest boxes, including up to 36% parasitism and 20% other mortality for Xylocopa fenestrata; introduced earwigs and an introduced leafcutter bee frequently occupied boxes in one trial (47).\n- Ant exclusion increased productivity: excluding ants from solitary nests increased offspring production in a replicated controlled trial (46).\n- Suitability varies by substrate/species: most species used cavities in cut stems/tubes and drilled wooden blocks, but soil-filled nest boxes for Andrena flavipes were not occupied in one small trial (47).",
